Reordering the Middle East
President Bush, the Palestinian Prime Minister Mazen, and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into the American Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the Planning Staff at the U.S. Department of State, explains his "Roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What has been achieved in Iraq - and above all what the Iraqi people, with the help of the Americans, can now build on - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented, and peaceful Iraq could spur reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
However, it will take time for far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the Middle East to take hold.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security, economic, and political aspects.
Thanks to the pre-planning by the Americans and the rest of the world, and thanks to the rapid, focused, and goal-oriented intervention of the coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less severe than anticipated.
Hie und da gibt es Bedarf an humanitärer Hilfe, aber die angekündigte massive Krise ist glücklicherweise nie eingetreten.
Es gibt relativ wenige Flüchtlinge und Heimatvertriebene innerhalb des Irak. Die Versorgung mit Nahrungsmitteln, Wasser und Medikamenten ist in den meisten Fällen ausreichend oder bessert sich zumindest.
Die amerikanische Regierung hat über die UNO und Nichtregierungsorganisationen ungefähr 600 Millionen Dollar für unmittelbare humanitäre Hilfe zur Verfügung gestellt.
Überdies müssen wir im Irak die Grundordnung wiederherstellen.
Sicherheit ist die unabdingbare Voraussetzung für eine nachhaltige Verbesserung der Situation nach dem Krieg. Ohne Sicherheit können die Menschen ihr Land nicht wiederaufbauen, nicht zur Arbeit oder in Schulen zurückkehren.
After the fall of Saddam, there was a wave of looting, lawlessness, and settling of accounts.
Now, it is the top priority to bring an end to this violence.
Furthermore, it must be the task of international troops to secure and eliminate all weapons of mass destruction, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbors exacerbate the already fragile situation.
In the long term, we must help the Iraqis rebuild their police and military structures so that they can ensure their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be considered more accurately as economic renewal.
The physical capital is in better condition than expected, and the modern Iraq has a large reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, there are plenty of raw materials to process in Iraq.
The USA have made more than 2 billion dollars available to support the first reconstruction efforts.
Oil production is being increased to a better level.
To the longer-term challenges belong an increase in oil production and the reduction of Iraq's enormous debt.
The decision of the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographical, and political divides within Iraqi society, assistance in the political renewal of Iraq is likely the most difficult task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The American goal - an intact Iraq where the rule of law is respected and the government comes into being democratically - is no utopia, especially because Iraq has a well-educated population and a fairly large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue along the path it has already embarked upon and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be utilized.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have effects on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly any foreign policy issue that engages and polarizes public opinion as strongly as the Palestinian question.
Nearly a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the United States developed a roadmap that brings us progressively closer to this goal.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent a significant step in this direction.
Now, Palestinians and Israelis must be brought to start this process and take measures to improve the situation in order to subsequently tackle broader issues at the negotiation table.
Finally, it cannot be accepted that terrorists destroy the peace process forever.
However, a solution to the Palestinian question is not automatically also a solution to all problems in the Middle East.
Clearly and unambiguously are the challenges that Iran presents to us. This country is developing weapons of mass destruction and supports terrorism.
Such behavior mocks the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues on this path, it will have consequences.
If, however, one turns away from terrorism and the development of catastrophic weapons, the United States is willing to resume good relations with this country.
Just as the United States is willing to engage with Syria if there are substantial shifts in attitude there.
A more general issue is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
America tolerated the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East for too long.
As long as governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no incentive for outsiders to push for representative governance.
We have painfully come to realize that closed political systems lead to resentment and extremism against the interests of the United States, the West, and the entire world.
Therefore, we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East launched in December 2002 by Secretary of State Colin Powell.
Closed economic systems also pose a danger.
As indicated in last year's "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the Development Status of Arab Countries), Arab countries in the Middle East have lagged far behind other regions in areas such as personal freedom, women's rights, and economic and social development.
These countries have long had to watch as economic growth passed them by.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If his recently expressed proposal for a free trade zone between the United States and the Middle East were realized within a decade, it would provide a solid basis for such development.
